"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38101410/","38101410","2023","Integrated multi-omics profiling to dissect the spatiotemporal evolution of primary and metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma","Sun Y; Guo W; Wang Z; et al.","Cancer Cell","Original research (multi-omics, scRNA-seq + spatial)","10.1016/j.ccell.2023.11.010","48.8","Multi-region multi-omics (incl. scRNA-seq and spatial) across many paired primary/metastatic HCCs; shows high intratumor heterogeneity, subclonal selection during metastasis, and microenvironment features (activated fibroblasts, immunosuppressive B cells) associated with metastatic success."
"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35933472/","35933472","2022","A single-cell atlas of the multicellular ecosystem of primary and metastatic hepatocellular carcinoma","Lu Y; Yang A; Quan C; et al.","Nature Communications","Original research (single-cell atlas)","10.1038/s41467-022-32283-3","16.6","Large single-cell transcriptomic atlas mapping malignant, immune and stromal populations across primary and metastatic HCC; identifies TME subtypes and cell states linked to prognosis and potential therapeutic response."
"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36897840/","36897840","2023","Distinct single-cell immune ecosystems distinguish true and de novo HBV-related hepatocellular carcinoma recurrences","Chen S; Huang C; Liao G; et al.","Gut","Original research (single-cell immune profiling)","10.1136/gutjnl-2022-327989","31.2","Single-cell RNA-seq of HBV-related HCC reveals distinct immune ecosystem signatures between true recurrence and de novo tumors; implications for recurrence mechanisms and immunotherapy stratification."
"https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41617928/","41617928","2026","Large-scale single-cell analysis and in silico perturbation reveal dynamic evolution of HCC: from initiation to therapeutic targeting","Xia P; Shuang S; Fu D; et al.","NPJ Precision Oncology","Original research (large-scale single-cell + spatial)","10.1038/s41698-026-01307-2","6.8","Integrates large-scale single-cell and spatial profiling across HCC progression stages to map tumor cell states, immune/stromal niches, and nominate candidate therapeutic targets tied to resistance mechanisms."
